1
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:28,920
In the land of mountains, moorlands and lakes


2
00:00:28,920 --> 00:00:33,600
lies a valley of wide open spaces and fertile fields.


3
00:00:36,440 --> 00:00:41,120
This is the eastern corner
of Cumbria. Its farming heart.


4
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:43,280
I am in the Eden Valley.


5
00:00:43,280 --> 00:00:47,120
This place is sometimes called
Cumbria's best-kept secret.


6
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:50,680
But not any more. Thanks to the
World Sheepdog Trials, people


7
00:00:50,680 --> 00:00:54,240
have flocked here from all over the
globe to watch the experts at work.


8
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:59,840
High above the valley in the fells,
far away from the sheepdog trials,


9
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:04,640
I'll be getting a taste of sheep
farming at its most extreme.


10
00:01:04,640 --> 00:01:07,760
When the winds howl,
the rains pour and the snow falls,


11
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:10,480
life here can be pretty tough.


12
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:14,560
So, just how is this piece
of hi-tech kit going to help?


13
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:15,840
I'll be finding out.


14
00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:21,400
While back at the sheepdog trials,
just as the rain really gets going,


15
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:24,600
Helen and I go head-to-head
in a challenge of our own.


16
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:27,200
We've got this in the bag.


17
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,640
Farmer's daughter versus farmer's son.


18
00:01:30,720 --> 00:01:34,120
And I'll be taking a close look
at radical new proposals


19
00:01:34,120 --> 00:01:36,360
to change our planning laws.


20
00:01:36,360 --> 00:01:38,720
They could lead to many more houses being built.


21
00:01:38,720 --> 00:01:41,560
Would that ruin some lovely parts of our countryside


22
00:01:41,560 --> 00:01:45,320
or revive many rural communities?
That's what I'll be investigating.


23
00:01:45,320 --> 00:01:50,600
Also tonight, Adam's herd is facing
another test for bovine TB.


24
00:01:50,600 --> 00:01:55,400
He doesn't want to lose any cattle,
but one in particular is on his mind.


25
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:57,640
Eric has got a real place in my heart now.


26
00:01:57,640 --> 00:02:02,800
If he got TB and had to be put down,
that would bring a tear to my eye.


27
00:02:17,040 --> 00:02:19,760
The lush green slopes of the Eden Valley.


28
00:02:19,760 --> 00:02:22,600
A hidden jewel...


29
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:25,800
set between the rocky peaks
of its better-known neighbours,


30
00:02:25,800 --> 00:02:28,560
the Lake District and the Pennines.


31
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:34,320
And at the heart of the valley is
the 75,000 acre Lowther Estate.


32
00:02:34,320 --> 00:02:38,680
Today, the estate is host to
the World Sheepdog Trials,


33
00:02:38,680 --> 00:02:43,080
an international event that will
draw crowds of up to 40,000 people.


34
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:46,720
It's the latest event
in the estate's 800-year history.


35
00:02:48,600 --> 00:02:50,640
Once the Lowther Estate was so large,


36
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:53,360
you could walk from the east coast
to the west coast


37
00:02:53,360 --> 00:02:55,560
without ever leaving it.


38
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:59,480
But by 1957, life wasn't so sweet.


39
00:03:01,960 --> 00:03:04,000
In a bid to avoid inheritance tax,


40
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,760
the roof was stripped off this once
magnificent castle.


41
00:03:06,760 --> 00:03:09,720
The building, left to rack and ruin.


42
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:13,840
Now, thanks to a £9 million grant,
it has been restored and the rest


43
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:16,360
of the estate is not doing too bad either.


44
00:03:16,360 --> 00:03:20,720
I'm meeting estate manager
Richard Price to discover


45
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:24,280
how they are making this historic
estate fit for the 21st century.


46
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,120
Where is the money coming from
for all of this work?


47
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:32,560
The actual castle project is being
put into a trust,


48
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:34,800
the Lowther Castle Gardens Trust.


49
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:37,560
And the money for that is coming
from the public sector,


50
00:03:37,560 --> 00:03:41,320
large funding organisations like
the North West Development Agency


51
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:44,000
and things have moved forward very fast.


52
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,560
And very proud of what is happening with that.


53
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:51,200
It is very much the hub
and the crown of the estate.


54
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:54,640
And how much does having the
World Sheepdog Trials here help?


55
00:03:54,640 --> 00:03:57,880
It means a lot for the local community.


56
00:03:57,880 --> 00:03:59,600
It brings a lot of income
into the local community.


57
00:04:01,520 --> 00:04:04,720
While the World Sheepdog Trials
are bringing 240 shepherds


58
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:07,560
from around the world to Lowther,


59
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:10,520
they do have plenty of their own
sheep to look after.


60
00:04:10,520 --> 00:04:14,640
The estate runs 5,000 of these mule sheep.


61
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:17,680
They have a hardy Swaledale mum
and a lean, muscly,


62
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:21,160
Blue-faced Leicester dad making them
rugged for this environment,


63
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:22,600
but ideal for the table.


64
00:04:25,400 --> 00:04:27,800
John Harrison is the estate's head shepherd.


65
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:30,400
He's working hard behind the scenes to get


66
00:04:30,400 --> 00:04:34,080
the huge amounts of sheep ready,
in the right place for the trials.


67
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:39,480
So, John, are you tempted to have
a go at the trials this year


68
00:04:39,480 --> 00:04:42,280
because you could?
Former English national champion.


69
00:04:42,280 --> 00:04:44,800
Well, I mean, it would be nice to but I haven't


70
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:46,720
competed for about 10 or 12 years now,


71
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:48,560
so I've probably lost the edge.


72
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:51,160
It would be nice to have a go,
I must be honest.


73
00:04:51,160 --> 00:04:54,000
Sure. There are handlers coming
from all over the world.


74
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,560
I'm not sure what they'll make of the mules.


75
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:58,840
It will be interesting to find out really.


76
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:01,320
The interesting thing is, every handler


77
00:05:01,320 --> 00:05:03,160
gets a different set of sheep.


78
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:06,040
This is a nightmare for you
to keep things moving around?


79
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:10,200
We have over 1,200 sheep to get ready
for the trials in the next four days.


80
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:12,240
Luckily, we have a good, strong committee


81
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:14,280
and a lot of helpers to help as well.


82
00:05:14,280 --> 00:05:16,240
There is a lot of work involved,


83
00:05:16,240 --> 00:05:19,000
early mornings and late nights unfortunately.


84
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:22,040
What does it mean to you as head
shepherd to have the world trials?


85
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:24,160
It's tremendous that it has come here.


86
00:05:24,160 --> 00:05:26,120
And also for the local environment.


87
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:29,240
You know, with all the people
coming in and the local community,


88
00:05:29,240 --> 00:05:31,320
it is fantastic for that as well.


89
00:05:31,320 --> 00:05:35,840
Back at the trials,
the competition is well under way.


90
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:38,520
I have arranged to meet up with
Katy Cropper who won


91
00:05:38,520 --> 00:05:40,960
One Man And His Dog in 1990.


92
00:05:40,960 --> 00:05:44,960
'Well done, lass, that is
what I call a good trial.'


93
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:46,600
The first woman to do so.


94
00:05:46,600 --> 00:05:49,920
Katy, here is the BBC Television trophy.


95
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:52,120
That is something to keep, isn't it?


96
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:53,760
Wonderful, wait a minute.


97
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:57,680
She now lives and works right on
the doorstep in the Eden Valley.


98
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:01,680
What a wonderful thing to have the
World Sheepdog Trials here.


99
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:04,120
Yes, it's gorgeous.
This is God's country.


100
00:06:04,120 --> 00:06:07,000
As you can see, it's the
most stunning, stunning scenery.


101
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,080
The trial field looks fantastic.


102
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:11,000
There is a tremendous feel to it.


103
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,040
It couldn't be more perfect for
the trial. It is not easy.


104
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:16,200
Field number one is quite a tricky course.


105
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:18,880
Some of those sheep are quite contrary.


106
00:06:18,880 --> 00:06:22,080
I actually did the course
the night before the actual trial.


107
00:06:22,080 --> 00:06:23,400
How was it?


108
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:27,080
Lovely. I think I should have won it!


109
00:06:27,080 --> 00:06:30,680
There are some right rough ground
going from the shedding ring


110
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:34,120
to the pen so you wouldn't be wanting
to wear your Jimmy Choos


111
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:36,120
because it really is quite rough.


112
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:38,960
But for the dogs and the handlers, that win this,


113
00:06:38,960 --> 00:06:42,120
it is a big deal, isn't it,
the World Championships?


114
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:43,520
Fantastic!


115
00:06:43,520 --> 00:06:46,360
And it can be quite lucrative.
Oh, I'm sure.


116
00:06:46,360 --> 00:06:49,040
Depending on who the person is that
wins with their dog,


117
00:06:49,040 --> 00:06:53,320
you never know,
the dog will be worth a lot of money.


118
00:06:53,320 --> 00:06:57,600
We've got the best dogs and the best
handlers from all over the world.


119
00:06:58,840 --> 00:07:00,800
But not the best of the weather.


120
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:03,280
Heavy rain is affecting the trials.


121
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:06,560
Later I'll be meeting a couple
of the international competitors


122
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:08,480
who have braved the Cumbrian climate.


123
00:07:11,200 --> 00:07:14,640
In just a couple of weeks' time,
the Government's consultation


124
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:18,520
on making radical changes to
our planning rules comes to an end.


125
00:07:18,520 --> 00:07:21,040
The proposals couldn't be more controversial.


126
00:07:21,040 --> 00:07:25,000
But what difference will they really
make? John has been to investigate.


127
00:07:31,560 --> 00:07:35,680
England's planning laws rose
out of the ashes of World War II,


128
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:39,120
to prevent a free-for-all in building.


129
00:07:39,120 --> 00:07:42,800
But fast-forward to today
and they've created a bureaucracy


130
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:44,880
with 1,300 pages of planning guidance,


131
00:07:44,880 --> 00:07:50,440
causing delays which cost the economy
an estimated £3 billion every year.


132
00:07:50,440 --> 00:07:55,080
Now, the Government has decided it's time 
to speed up the whole planning process,


133
00:07:55,080 --> 00:08:00,040
in a bid to get more homes built
and kick-start the economy.


134
00:08:00,040 --> 00:08:04,000
All those pages of guidance
will be cut to just 52.


135
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,880
But these proposals have
exploded into a war of words


136
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:12,320
between ministers
and deeply concerned heritage groups.


137
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:15,040
The protection for the green belt...


138
00:08:15,040 --> 00:08:19,080
I'm not a left-winger.
I'm not a fanatical.


139
00:08:19,080 --> 00:08:22,000
..rather than replacing...


140
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,080
What's causing the uproar is
the Government's idea that


141
00:08:25,080 --> 00:08:28,560
councils should have a presumption
in favour of what they call


142
00:08:28,560 --> 00:08:31,120
sustainable development.
In other words,


143
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:35,920
they should be more likely to approve
new housing than turn it down.


144
00:08:35,920 --> 00:08:39,040
So, would these new laws ride
roughshod over the countryside,


145
00:08:39,040 --> 00:08:43,160
or would they throw a vital
lifeline to rural communities


146
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:46,360
with an uncertain future?


147
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:49,680
To try to shed some light on
what the proposals could mean,


148
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:54,880
we've picked two villages in Somerset with 
very different prospects for the future.


149
00:08:54,880 --> 00:08:57,680
First, East Coker in the south of the county,


150
00:08:57,680 --> 00:09:01,600
a quintessentially English village.


151
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:04,520
Good morning, John.
Good morning, what a beautiful day.


152
00:09:04,520 --> 00:09:08,080
1,400 people live here
including Martin Sowerbutts


153
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:10,560
who is taking me on a visit to the local church.


154
00:09:13,320 --> 00:09:14,480
Here we are, John.


155
00:09:14,480 --> 00:09:17,760
If we go up the tower I can show you
what we are talking about.


156
00:09:17,760 --> 00:09:19,080
Right up the top, there.


157
00:09:19,080 --> 00:09:22,360
'But we're not just heading up high
to get a bird's-eye view


158
00:09:22,360 --> 00:09:25,120
'of this lovely village of 900 homes.'


159
00:09:25,120 --> 00:09:27,720
Many more to go?


160
00:09:27,720 --> 00:09:30,720
About halfway I should say, John.


161
00:09:30,720 --> 00:09:35,360
Martin wants to show me a development
site for up to 3,700 houses


162
00:09:35,360 --> 00:09:38,840
which could be built right on their doorsteps.


163
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:41,560
Well worth the climb! What a view!


164
00:09:41,560 --> 00:09:42,920
Fantastic, isn't it?


165
00:09:44,920 --> 00:09:48,720
So where exactly is this proposed
development going to be?


166
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:52,240
You see the brown field ahead of us,
it will span across there,


167
00:09:52,240 --> 00:09:53,960
to the left, behind this tree.


168
00:09:53,960 --> 00:09:55,840
To the outskirts of Yeovil?


169
00:09:55,840 --> 00:09:58,280
It will join on to the outskirts of Yeovil


170
00:09:58,280 --> 00:10:01,040
and go right across to the houses on the horizon.


171
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:04,840
It will look like, essentially,
gravy pouring down from Yeovil


172
00:10:04,840 --> 00:10:07,120
into the Vale of East Coker.


173
00:10:07,120 --> 00:10:10,720
All the area they're going to build
on is grade 1 agricultural land.


174
00:10:10,720 --> 00:10:13,040
The finest and most fertile available.


175
00:10:13,040 --> 00:10:18,200
It accounts for something less than 5% 
of all agricultural land in England.


176
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:21,200
And to build on that,
well, I think it's criminal.


177
00:10:21,200 --> 00:10:24,360
Although sites like green belts
will still be protected,


178
00:10:24,360 --> 00:10:28,840
proposals to defend premium farmland 
like this have yet to be approved,


179
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:31,200
leaving them at risk of development.


180
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:32,840
Many see East Coker's case


181
00:10:32,840 --> 00:10:37,080
as the sort of battle that could
take place right across the country,


182
00:10:37,080 --> 00:10:38,680
if the new changes go through.


183
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:42,520
To give you some idea of the effect 
it'd have, I have a photograph here


184
00:10:42,520 --> 00:10:47,520
which gives a representation of what it would 
look like if this development went ahead.


185
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:52,320
You can see all of the houses here
would be covering that area there.


186
00:10:52,320 --> 00:10:57,480
'Although this artist's impression has been 
done for those opposed to the development,


187
00:10:57,480 --> 00:11:00,960
'it's undeniable that this many
houses will have a dramatic impact.'


188
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:04,080
So how far
is this village going to take it?


189
00:11:04,080 --> 00:11:07,840
Well, we didn't want it, but we think 
in some ways we're a test case.


190
00:11:07,840 --> 00:11:12,280
With all the assets East Coker
has got, the heritage, the farming,


191
00:11:12,280 --> 00:11:16,520
the quality of the land, if we can't
actually make our case stick,


192
00:11:16,520 --> 00:11:19,640
then we think that nowhere
in the country's going to be safe,


193
00:11:19,640 --> 00:11:22,040
particularly under the new planning framework.


194
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:29,320
The Government says new planning guidelines will 
put power back in the hands of local people.


195
00:11:29,320 --> 00:11:32,440
Here, in South Somerset,
they're not so sure about that.


196
00:11:32,440 --> 00:11:36,920
The woman who represents East Coker
on the district council


197
00:11:36,920 --> 00:11:41,040
says her colleagues have little alternative
but to do what the Government wants.


198
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:46,000
My preference would have been to spread 
the houses amongst the villages,


199
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,600
because I believe that protects the school,


200
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:50,120
the shops and the pub


201
00:11:50,120 --> 00:11:52,320
and other community facilities,


202
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:55,640
but what the Government wants
is to have the development


203
00:11:55,640 --> 00:11:58,000
on the edge of towns with employment land


204
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:02,720
and with retail provision within
that area along with the houses,


205
00:12:02,720 --> 00:12:06,240
and so that is what the district 
council's had to put into their plan.


206
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:10,480
What you're saying is, it's not
really your local district plan,


207
00:12:10,480 --> 00:12:14,040
it's a plan that the Government
is imposing on you.


208
00:12:14,040 --> 00:12:17,480
Certainly, if we don't have
a local plan which goes this way,


209
00:12:17,480 --> 00:12:19,840
developers will be able to come along and say,


210
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:22,720
we are going to develop here, or wherever,


211
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:24,640
and we won't be able to refuse them


212
00:12:24,640 --> 00:12:28,760
because we haven't identified somewhere 
else more suitable for them to go.


213
00:12:28,760 --> 00:12:32,200
I certainly don't want it to be
a free-for-all for developers.


214
00:12:32,200 --> 00:12:35,680
The council say the development
would bring benefits to the area,


215
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:39,640
but can't be specific
until plans are finalised.


216
00:12:39,640 --> 00:12:42,600
So are existing businesses
positive about the proposals?


217
00:12:42,600 --> 00:12:45,600
Good morning. Hello there.


218
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:49,920
Could I have the local paper, please?
No problem. That's 70 pence, please.


219
00:12:49,920 --> 00:12:54,000
I suppose you'll be glad when the new
houses are put up, good for business?


220
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:56,240
No, we don't think so, actually.


221
00:12:56,240 --> 00:12:58,880
We believe with the size of
the estate it's going to be,


222
00:12:58,880 --> 00:13:00,760
they'll bring shops with them,


223
00:13:00,760 --> 00:13:06,240
possibly a mini supermarket,
and we think it's going to
draw customers away from us.


224
00:13:06,240 --> 00:13:10,960
'In East Coker, it's hard to
find people in favour of
the proposed development,


225
00:13:10,960 --> 00:13:14,680
'and that's the big concern about
these possible planning changes,


226
00:13:14,680 --> 00:13:16,960
'that they
simply won't take into account


227
00:13:16,960 --> 00:13:21,080
'the views of local people
if they're against development.'


228
00:13:23,040 --> 00:13:28,160
But in other places, there are those
who believe these plans
could actually work in their favour.


229
